        <div class='o-col-oneWhole _lg-o-col-twoThirds u-mt4'>
          <p class='s-h3'>
            Ever since my father put an Olympus Stylus Epic into my then-adolescent hands, I have been a lover of photography.
          </p>
          <p>
            To borrow a phrase from Garry Winogrand, I believe that there is nothing so mysterious as a fact clearly described. I have spent many an hour over the past years on the streets of London and other locations in Europe and Canada, capturing spontaneous moments in an ongoing series of images which attempt to record these mysteries of facts, and to understand how a photograph both reflects and transforms what is captured within its&nbsp;perimeters.
          </p>
          <p>
            While my photographic interests are primarily aesthetic, my ongoing desire is to present an alternative view of reality which might otherwise remain invisible, or considered unremarkable or banal. Within the chaos of daily life, it is my hope that a measure of fascination might be uncovered and&nbsp;appreciated.
          <p>
          <p>
            I released <a href='images-pour-rien.html'>‘Images Pour Rien’, my first book of photographs</a>, in early 2016 (and a redesigned, abridged second edition is on the way). I am currently working on developing a new body of work, and taking on the occasional commission for&nbsp;publications.
          </p>

